<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ProcessDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-TU7HddOG-v1SZ2NJsT1nGg" name="cots_inception_define_candidate_solutions,_P6-zYffeEdmriJhf4djjLA" guid="-TU7HddOG-v1SZ2NJsT1nGg" version="7.1.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Once the information has been gathered within each sphere of influence, the goal is to manage the interaction and&#xD;
    integration of the information. The focus is now on identifying and resolving mismatches across the information, and on&#xD;
    combining the information to form a candidate solution that meet the demands of the most critical use cases and&#xD;
    non-functional requirements, architectural and design constraints, and project management constraints such as time,&#xD;
    money, people, and scope, with reasonable risks. These tasks require a heavy involvement from all the stakeholders (or&#xD;
    empowered representatives) that must be at the center of the negotiation process and hence drive the forming of the&#xD;
    candidate solution.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A solution is the integrated assembly of one or more COTS packages or COTS package components, legacy systems (piece of&#xD;
    the systems being replaced), reuse libraries, other reuse sources (e.g., freeware, shareware), any required custom code&#xD;
    (including wrappers and &quot;glue&quot;), appropriate linkage to the broader organization's architecture with which the solution&#xD;
    must interface, and changes to the user business processes necessary to match the processes provided in the COTS&#xD;
    packages. In this phase, a reasonable number of solutions will be formed based on the gathered information; these&#xD;
    solutions will be considered candidates until one is selected in the elaboration phase.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The important areas of work to define a candidate solution, negotiate tradeoffs and demonstrate the feasibility of the&#xD;
    solution are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Define Solution&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The objective is to combine the information gathered from the four spheres of influence to form (or update) a candidate&#xD;
    solution. This is done by cycling through the following steps (see &lt;a href=&quot;#note&quot;>&lt;em>&lt;strong>Note&lt;/strong>&lt;/em>&lt;/a>&#xD;
    below): &lt;strong>Perform Gap Analysis&lt;/strong>, &lt;strong>Negotiate Tradeoffs&lt;/strong>, &lt;strong>Form Solution&lt;/strong> and&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Score Solution&lt;/strong>. The preceding steps were presented in a logical order; however you may need to&#xD;
    alternate between them or perform some of them in parallel.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;p>&#xD;
            &lt;b>Perform Gap Analysis:&lt;/b> This step is done through a pair-wise comparison of the COTS packages identified&#xD;
            in the context of the &quot;marketplace&quot; sphere to the information gathered from the &quot;architecture and design&quot;,&#xD;
            &quot;stakeholder needs and business processes&quot; and &quot;programmatics and risks&quot; spheres. The focus is on trying to&#xD;
            understand where they match, where they don't match, and a characterization of the mismatches.&#xD;
        &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;p>&#xD;
            &lt;b>Negotiate Tradeoffs:&lt;/b> This is a key step to make sure that any identified mismatch is understood and&#xD;
            resolved. It is imperative to understand how important each mismatch is to the solution and understand the&#xD;
            possible ways the mismatch can be resolved. Mismatches can be resolved through negotiating with stakeholders to&#xD;
            modify user business processes and stated stakeholder needs; gathering more information about the capabilities&#xD;
            of the COTS packages and their ability to be tailored to accommodate the mismatch; changing the way the&#xD;
            architecture uses the COTS packages; or creating a custom component to provide the necessary capability. If a&#xD;
            mismatch cannot be sufficiently resolved, the candidate solution may be removed from further consideration.&#xD;
        &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Form Solution:&lt;/b> With an understanding of the matches and mismatches, a candidate solution is formed (or&#xD;
        updated) by assembling one or more COTS packages or COTS package components, legacy systems (piece of the systems&#xD;
        being replaced), reuse libraries, other reuse sources (e.g., freeware, shareware), any required custom code&#xD;
        (including wrappers and &quot;glue&quot;) and appropriate linkage to the broader organization's architecture with which the&#xD;
        solution must interface. An architectural design overview is produced for the candidate solution that encompasses a&#xD;
        high-level &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_design_model_2830034D.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;{8CDAEAD4-5E84-4F50-87FD-3240ED047DE7}&quot;>Design Model&lt;/a>, a high-level &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_software_architecture_document_C367485C.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;{6F49641A-ED10-47B5-9E5D-3F90A6BF3006}&quot;>Software Architecture Document&lt;/a> and a high-level &lt;a&#xD;
        class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_deployment_model_57DF1DF5.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;{5981B6BE-2FD1-4984-AA94-2F7428439BA6}&quot;>Deployment Model&lt;/a>. &#xD;
        &lt;p>&#xD;
            &lt;i>&lt;b>&lt;a id=&quot;note&quot; name=&quot;note&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;/b>&lt;strong>Note&lt;/strong>&lt;b>:&lt;/b>&lt;/i> In the &lt;strong>Perform Gap&#xD;
            Analysis&lt;/strong> step, the pair-wise comparison does not have to focus on all the spheres at the same time.&#xD;
            For instance, the step could start by comparing the identified COTS packages to the information gathered from&#xD;
            the &quot;architecture and design&quot; sphere only, in order to access how each COTS package fits into the enterprise&#xD;
            architecture. Based on this information some tradeoffs could be negotiated and some solutions formed. Then the&#xD;
            information gathered from the &quot;stakeholder needs and business processes&quot; sphere could be added in order to&#xD;
            assess how each COTS package supports the required user business processes. Based on this information some&#xD;
            tradeoffs could be negotiated and the solutions refined. This process continues until candidate solutions are&#xD;
            formed (or updated) based on all the available information gathered from the spheres.&#xD;
        &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Score Solution:&lt;/b> The goal is to score the candidate solution against the project's constraints, including&#xD;
        most critical use cases and non-functional requirements, architectural and design constraints, project management&#xD;
        constraints and any constraint related to business processes. The rating is done by using &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_requirements_attributes_EFE5ABAC.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;{D0E2E7A1-4179-470E-AA18-419D5FEA275D}&quot;>Requirements Attributes&lt;/a>. Again, involving all stakeholders (or&#xD;
        empowered representatives) is highly recommended while performing this step in order to gather as much feedback as&#xD;
        possible on the candidate solution.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The definition of a candidate solution is captured in a &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.cots/workproducts/cots_solution_dossier_54E01F3A.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{4F2452F1-8664-4198-A228-72A12745079D}&quot;>Solution Dossier&lt;/a> that includes the relevant &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.cots/workproducts/cots_package_dossier_F44E6C04.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{B8F591A5-DA8E-4CC6-A41E-DD522B6C1102}&quot;>COTS Package Dossier(s)&lt;/a>, &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.cots/workproducts/cots_vendor_dossier_9DDAD3A2.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{E6CEF5C2-2915-48D6-8607-D83489CC101E}&quot;>Vendor Dossier(s)&lt;/a>, and the architectural design overview (&lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_design_model_2830034D.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{8CDAEAD4-5E84-4F50-87FD-3240ED047DE7}&quot;>Design Model&lt;/a>&lt;i>,&lt;/i> &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_software_architecture_document_C367485C.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{6F49641A-ED10-47B5-9E5D-3F90A6BF3006}&quot;>Software Architecture Document&lt;/a> and &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_deployment_model_57DF1DF5.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{5981B6BE-2FD1-4984-AA94-2F7428439BA6}&quot;>Deployment Model&lt;/a>), as well as the values given in the &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_requirements_attributes_EFE5ABAC.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{D0E2E7A1-4179-470E-AA18-419D5FEA275D}&quot;>Requirements Attributes&lt;/a> for the solution. Other artifacts may be&#xD;
    updated while defining a candidate solution due to the negotiation process. For instance if the stakeholders decide to&#xD;
    change some user business processes the To-Be &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.bus_model/workproducts/rup_business_use_case_model_EC79264C.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{89BEF367-5875-47E0-97D6-23E5BCCE52B8}&quot;>Business Use Case Model&lt;/a> (and any other derived artifacts) should be&#xD;
    updated accordingly.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Defining a given candidate solution is done by completing the RUP task shown in the following figure (note that other&#xD;
    RUP tasks and artifacts may be applicable, but this is the minimum recommended set):&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;Content described in text&quot; src=&quot;resources/Out1_Define_Solutions.gif&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    Because the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.cots/roles/cots_system_architect_9FFD10CA.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{1D3A4C45-97FC-491F-8580-523E3AC5887E}&quot;>System Architect's&lt;/a> view is broad and spans the entire system, the &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../extend.cots/roles/cots_system_architect_9FFD10CA.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{1D3A4C45-97FC-491F-8580-523E3AC5887E}&quot;>System Architect&lt;/a> rarely engages in depth in the detailed engineering&#xD;
    of a system, preferring to leave that to other practitioners in the various engineering specialties. For instance, in&#xD;
    order to define candidate solutions, the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.cots/roles/cots_system_architect_9FFD10CA.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{1D3A4C45-97FC-491F-8580-523E3AC5887E}&quot;>System Architect&lt;/a> needs to collaborate with a set of supporting roles:&#xD;
    &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../extend.bus_model/roles/rup_business_process_analyst_B9668ABF.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{76FAC4FE-AA09-48AC-85A5-68BD1EE8A86A}&quot;>Business Process Analyst&lt;/a>, &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/roles/rup_system_analyst_C3C9C9AC.html&quot; guid=&quot;{F1F206DF-3AA0-4AC0-92EF-8E4A01B6C5B5}&quot;>System&#xD;
    Analyst&lt;/a>&lt;i>,&lt;/i> &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/roles/rup_project_manager_363CE680.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{EE97A8CD-66CA-4A9B-9871-E3B94CCED528}&quot;>Project Manager&lt;/a>, &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/roles/rup_software_architect_DB0BF177.html&quot; guid=&quot;{4AC346F0-E6FC-4D2C-8410-2EDF8DDDC91D}&quot;>Software&#xD;
    Architect&lt;/a>, and &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../extend.cots/roles/cots_acquirer_FA0DC38C.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{E929498F-3E9B-4BD5-8FD3-FAF7337E36AE}&quot;>Acquirer&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Demonstrate Candidate Solution Feasibility&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The objective is to demonstrate the feasibility of a candidate solution by refining the architectural design overview&#xD;
    for the solution, building an architectural proof-of-concept based on this overview and assessing the viability of this&#xD;
    architectural proof-of-concept. An architectural proof-of-concept may take many forms, like a simulation of a solution&#xD;
    or an executable prototype. The architectural proof-of-concept is assessed against the architecturally significant&#xD;
    requirements gathered from the spheres. Even though this area of work falls under the responsibility of the software&#xD;
    architect, it is recommended to start involving key implementers and testers so they get a sense for what will be&#xD;
    implemented and tested as soon as possible in the project. The architectural proof-of-concept also helps the&#xD;
    stakeholders, who must be involved in the assessment process, better understand the changes to the user business&#xD;
    processes associated with the candidate solution.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural design overview for the candidate solution is refined as an element of the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.cots/workproducts/cots_solution_dossier_54E01F3A.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{4F2452F1-8664-4198-A228-72A12745079D}&quot;>Solution Dossier&lt;/a>. This architectural design overview encompasses a&#xD;
    high-level &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_design_model_2830034D.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{8CDAEAD4-5E84-4F50-87FD-3240ED047DE7}&quot;>Design Model&lt;/a>, a high-level &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_software_architecture_document_C367485C.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{6F49641A-ED10-47B5-9E5D-3F90A6BF3006}&quot;>Software Architecture Document&lt;/a> and a high-level &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_deployment_model_57DF1DF5.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{5981B6BE-2FD1-4984-AA94-2F7428439BA6}&quot;>Deployment Model&lt;/a>. This architectural design overview is used as an&#xD;
    input to create an &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_architectural_proof_of_concept_9AF95095.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{198EA2A5-4FBA-45D5-85BA-53B108728534}&quot;>Architectural Proof-of-Concept&lt;/a>. The assessment of the viability of&#xD;
    the architectural proof-of-concept for the candidate solution as well as any new information gathered about the&#xD;
    solution while demonstrating its feasibility are captured in its &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.cots/workproducts/cots_solution_dossier_54E01F3A.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{4F2452F1-8664-4198-A228-72A12745079D}&quot;>Solution Dossier&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Demonstrating the feasibility of a given candidate solution is done by performing the RUP tasks shown in the following&#xD;
    figure (note that other RUP tasks and artifacts may be applicable, but this is the minimum recommended set):&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;Content described in text&quot; src=&quot;resources/Out2_Proof_i.gif&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br /></mainDescription>
